<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910410-0081</DOCNO><DOCID>910410-0081.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Upjohn Co.:   Top Officers Are Rewarded   With Substantial Pay Raises</HL><DATE>04/10/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C8</SO><CO>   UPJ</CO><MS>CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)</MS><IN>DRUG MANUFACTURERS (DRG)</IN><RE>MICHIGAN (MI)</RE><LP>   Upjohn Co., which more than doubled its net income lastyear, rewarded its top officers with big pay increases,according to the company's proxy statement.   Theodore Cooper, chairman, president and chief executiveofficer, received $2.4 million in total compensation in 1990,a 30% increase from the previous year. His 1990 compensationincluded $1.3 million in cash compensation and more than $1million from exercising stock options.</LP><TEXT>   As a group, the company's top 11 executives received $4.8million in cash compensation last year and another $1.2million from exercising stock options.   Upjohn, a Kalamazoo, Mich.-based pharmaceutical concern,earned $446 million in 1990, up from $176 million in 1989.</TEXT></DOC>